{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17634318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17634318"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:58:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:58:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17510"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17510"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10200"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78188"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10200"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17510"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63594"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10064"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23869"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23886"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78188"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe inner mitochondrial membrane contains several protein complexes that form the electron transport chain, which is crucial for cellular respiration.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of Complex I in the electron transport chain?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oxidises NADH and transports protons","Oxidises succinate to fumarate","Converts oxygen to water","Transfers electrons from FADH2","Synthesizes ATP using proton gradient"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EComplex I (NADH dehydrogenase) \u003Cstrong\u003Eoxidises NADH and transports protons\u003C/strong\u003E from the matrix to the intermembrane space. This process initiates electron transport and contributes to the proton gradient used for ATP synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other components have different roles:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxidises succinate to fumarate\u003C/strong\u003E - This reaction occurs at Complex II (succinate dehydrogenase)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConverts oxygen to water\u003C/strong\u003E - Complex IV (cytochrome c oxidase) catalyzes this terminal reaction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfers electrons from FADH2\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a function of Complex II\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynthesises ATP using proton gradient\u003C/strong\u003E - ATP synthase (Complex V) performs this function\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe proton pumping activity of Complex I, along with Complexes III and IV, creates an electrochemical gradient across the inner membrane that drives ATP production through chemiosmosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Complex I (NADH dehydrogenase) is the first enzyme complex in the mitochondrial electron transport chain.","The primary role of Complex I is to oxidise NADH while simultaneously pumping protons across the inner membrane.","The proton gradient generated by Complex I and other complexes powers ATP synthesis through chemiosmosis."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Boron W. F., Boulpaep E. L. Medical Physiology. (3rd edition). US. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63594"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17510"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63594"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T17:40:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T17:41:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10200"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78188"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":nu